10616nam a22013215i 9783110701906DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020949175  a97831107019067 a10.1515/97831107019062doi  a(DE-B1597)549380  a(OCoLC)1233041156  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0170002bisacsh00aOur Lives - Our Stories: Life Experiences of Elderly Deaf People /cRoland Pfau, Asli Göksel, Jana Hosemann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XI, 416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSign Languages and Deaf Communities [SLDC] ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMuch more than a treasure: the life stories of elderly Deaf people -- tPart I: "For this experience, I am grateful to the elderly Deaf people": Collecting and disseminating life stories -- tConducting interviews with elderly Deaf people: opportunities and challenges -- tMaking the life stories of Deaf seniors visible: a students' exhibition -- tPart II: "I found out that deaf people could do many things": Issues of culture and identity -- tOnce upon a time: history and memory of Italian Deaf elderly signers -- tDeafness in Turkey 1930-2020: administrative, social, and cultural aspects -- tPink sign: identity challenges, choices, and changes among elderly Deaf homosexuals in the Netherlands -- tPart III: "Apparently, one could hear airplanes, but we knew nothing": Deaf lives in times of conflict and oppression -- tImpairment vs. disability: The paradoxical situation of deaf people during the German Nazi Regime -- tForced sterilization of deaf people during the German Nazi Regime - a trauma and its compensations after 1945 -- tSurviving a war of silence: Deaf people in Flanders during the Second World War -- tThe Francoist dictatorship through the Deaf lens -- tPart IV: "He signs like me, we are the same": Linguistic and educational perspectives -- tUncovering the lived experiences of elderly Deaf Philadelphians -- tTime will tell: time and discourse as 'motion through space' in early Israeli Sign Language (ISL) -- tPart V: "Goodbye, hearing world!": Creating a safe environment for the elderly Deaf -- tDe Gelderhorst: a home full of signs -- tGrowing old together: aging deaf people and the politics of belonging -- tList of contributors -- tSubject index -- tName index (incl. associations, laws, and schools)0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSign languages are non-written languages. Given that the use of digital media and video recordings in documenting sign languages started only some 30 years ago, the life stories of Deaf elderly signers born in the 1930s-1940s have - except for a few scattered fragments in film - not been documented and are therefore under serious threat of being lost.The chapters compiled in this volume document important aspects of past and present experiences of elderly Deaf signers across Europe, as well as in Israel and the United States. Issues addressed include (i) historical events and how they were experienced by Deaf people, (ii) issues of identity and independence, (iii) aspects of language change, (iv) experiences of suppression and discrimination. The stories shared by elderly signers reveal intriguing, yet hidden, aspects of Deaf life. On the negative side, these include experiences of the Deaf in Nazi Germany and occupied countries and harsh practices in educational settings, to name a few. On the positive side, there are stories of resilience and vivid memories of school years and social and professional life.In this way, the volume contributes in a significant way to the preservation of the cultural and linguistic heritage of Deaf communities and sheds light on lesser known aspects against an otherwise familiar background. This publication has been made possible within the SIGN-HUB project, which has received funding from the European Union's Horizon 2020 research and innovation programme.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 4aGehörlos. 4aZeichensprache. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Sign Language.2bisacsh  aDeaf Community.  aDeaf Culture.  aElderly People.  aSign Language.1 aAliaga, Delfina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarberà, Gemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockmann, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusto, Raquel Veiga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCramer, Jens-Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDachkovsky, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemirel, Buket Ela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDes Dorides, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDikyuva, Hasan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Jami N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGöksel, Asli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGöksel, Aslı, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarterink, Menno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiddinga, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochgesang, Julie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosemann, Jana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosemann, Jana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKozelka, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller,